From 549482bdb007879c640c1949df0cc9b7e307d389 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: patamin-lab <patamin@gmail.com>
Date: Wed, 24 Jun 2026 13:08:14 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Fix Drive uploads: switch service-account auth to OAuth2

Live deploy hit 'Service Accounts do not have storage quota' on every
upload. Root cause: the destination Drive folder lives in a personal
Gmail account, not Google Workspace - personal accounts have no
Shared Drives and no domain-wide delegation, so a service account
(which owns zero storage of its own) can never write into it, Editor
sharing or not. This is a hard Google platform limitation, not
something fixable by changing how the upload code calls the API.

Fix: authenticate as the real Gmail account via OAuth2 + a refresh
token instead of a service account, so uploads are attributed to that
account's own (free, plenty for this use case) storage quota.

- src/lib/googleDrive.ts: driveClient() now builds a
  google.auth.OAuth2 client from CLIENT_ID/CLIENT_SECRET/REFRESH_TOKEN
  instead of a JWT service-account client. Folder lookup/create,
  upload, public-permission, and relocate logic are unchanged - only
  the auth strategy changed.
- scripts/get-google-refresh-token.mjs (new): one-time local helper
  the dealer runs themselves (never sends the token through anyone but
  Google) to mint the refresh token. Opens a consent URL, catches the
  redirect on a local loopback server, prints the refresh token to
  mint into GOOGLE_OAUTH_REFRESH_TOKEN.
- package.json: added 'npm run drive:auth' shortcut for the script.

Env vars now needed (replaces the old service-account vars):
  GOOGLE_OAUTH_CLIENT_ID
  GOOGLE_OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET
  GOOGLE_OAUTH_REFRESH_TOKEN  (minted via scripts/get-google-refresh-token.mjs)
  GOOGLE_DRIVE_ROOT_FOLDER_ID (folder ID in that account's own My Drive)
